data.title: Top 500 Greatest ALbums of the 1960s
data.meta_description: I just bought this magazine, from The Ultimate Record Collection. I bought it on a whim, not really expecting anything from it. Having said this, it surprised me; it is a really well-curated list of top records from the 1960s, ranked in order and very eclectic in what is includes. It has made me return to that music, purchase albums I did not buy back in the day, and I enjoyed reading the entries they have for each record on the list. It includes everything from rock, folk, jazz (trad and out),
data.text:
I just got it today. I played it while having dinner and thought it was really an excellent folk record, but one that incorporated strings, like you said, and his voice is recognizable as the later singer in QMS. Nice disc!

SS- though I have told the tale many times, I saw the Stooges (when they were the Psychedelic Stooges) and the MC5 open for Blue Cheer at the Grande Ballroom, in what was the loudest show I have ever attended (I was not yet old enough to drive). My take is that the MC5 blew both bands not just off stage but pretty much out of the universe, and I say this having enjoyed all 3 bands. BTW, my ears rang for weeks after that show. Not joking. Neither Hendrix nor Mahavishnu were ever as loud as that show, nor was Magma or the Tony Williams Lifetime.

I found that font/background combination very tough on the eyes. so...
